{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525177"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14063"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14063"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.82,0.06,0.03,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109890"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6717"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92251"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1459"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45741"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109890"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 80-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of fatigue, dizziness, and two episodes of syncope. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include ramipril and paracetamol. She does not smoke or drink alcohol. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 42/min and regular, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals normal heart sounds with no murmurs. A 12-lead ECG shows sinus bradycardia with a rate of 40 beats per minute with a normal QRS duration and no axis deviation (Image). A 24-hour Holter monitor reveals periods of sinus bradycardia with pauses up to 4 seconds during the day which have been correlated with symptoms of dizziness. The holter has detected episode of paroxysmal atrial fibrillation lasting for less than 30 seconds at a time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Referral for pacemaker implantation","Initiation of beta-blocker therapy","Exercise stress test","Carotid sinus massage","Loop recorder insertion for further monitoring"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with sick sinus syndrome, also known as sinus node dysfunction. The most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral for pacemaker implantation\u003C/strong\u003E. Sick sinus syndrome is characterized by inappropriate sinus bradycardia, sinus pauses, or chronotropic incompetence, often accompanied by paroxysmal atrial tachyarrhythmias. The patient\u0027s symptoms of fatigue, dizziness, and syncope, along with the ECG findings of sinus bradycardia and the Holter monitor results showing alternating bradycardia and atrial fibrillation, strongly support this diagnosis. Current guidelines stipulate permanent pacemaker is recommended in patients with spontaneous documented symptomatic asytolic pause/s \u0026gt;3 s or asymptomatic pause/s \u0026gt;6 s due to sinus arrest or AVB; or cardioinhibitory carotid sinus syndrome; or asystolic syncope during tilt testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid sinus massage\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. It is typically used to diagnose carotid sinus hypersensitivity or to terminate supraventricular tachycardias. In a patient with suspected sick sinus syndrome, carotid sinus massage could potentially exacerbate bradycardia and is not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitiation of \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta-blocker therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in this patient. Beta-blockers slow the heart rate and could worsen the bradycardia associated with sick sinus syndrome, potentially leading to more severe symptoms or complications. beta-blockers can be used for the atrial fibrillation if there is a fast ventricular response after the permanent placement is inserted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELoop recorder insertion can be considered with diagnosis is unclear and there is conduction disease no baseline ECG for a patient who presents with multiple syncopes, this device does not prevent the syncope but does record the rhythm during the syncope so we would be able to decide if the syncope if related to the cardiac rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eexercise stress test\u003C/strong\u003E might be useful in assessing chronotropic incompetence, which can be a feature of sick sinus syndrome. However, given the patient\u0027s symptoms and the clear evidence of sinus node dysfunction on ECG and Holter monitoring, a stress test is not necessary before proceeding with definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPacemaker implantation is the definitive treatment for symptomatic sick sinus syndrome. It will help regulate the patient\u0027s heart rhythm, prevent bradycardia-related symptoms, and allow for the safe use of medications to manage the atrial fibrillation if needed. After pacemaker implantation, the patient\u0027s symptoms of fatigue, dizziness, and syncope should improve significantly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sick sinus syndrome is characterized by inappropriate sinus bradycardia, sinus pauses, or chronotropic incompetence.","Symptoms of sick sinus syndrome include fatigue, dizziness, and syncope.","Pacemaker implantation is the definitive treatment for symptomatic sick sinus syndrome with symptoms and severe bradycardia with pauses"],"references":["2021 ESC Guidelines on cardiac pacing and cardiac resynchronization therapy"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92251"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14063"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20971"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20971"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JvhPXvN9itVJpoqrltA0PHXumNa391.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JvhPXvN9itVJpoqrltA0PHXumNa391.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":289}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92251"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T14:00:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T14:00:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6717"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109890"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"